WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:04.170 --> 00:00:07.040 align:start size:97% position:3%
Allie Nimmons: Hello,
everyone, welcome to WordPress

00:00:07.073 --> 00:00:08.474
Accessibility Day.

00:00:08.507 --> 00:00:10.076
My name is Allie Nimmons.

00:00:10.109 --> 00:00:11.711 align:start size:84% position:16%
I'm your host for
the next few sessions.

00:00:11.744 --> 00:00:14.447
We're about to get started with
the very first session of the

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:17.050
event, "So How Do I Know
If My WordPress Website

00:00:17.083 --> 00:00:20.119 align:start size:84% position:16%
Is Accessible?"
with Graham Armfield.

00:00:20.152 --> 00:00:21.821
So if that's a question that
you've asked yourself before,

00:00:21.854 --> 00:00:23.656
you are in the right place.

00:00:23.689 --> 00:00:26.159
Please feel free to add your
questions directly into the

00:00:26.192 --> 00:00:28.661 align:start size:94% position:6%
YouTube chat feed, and we'll
answer those together

00:00:28.694 --> 00:00:30.463
at the end of the presentation.

00:00:30.496 --> 00:00:33.132
A little bit about Graham:
Graham is a web accessibility

00:00:33.165 --> 00:00:36.402 align:start position:0%
consultant with his own
company, Coolfields Consulting.

00:00:36.435 --> 00:00:38.604
He works with organizations
to help them improve the

00:00:38.637 --> 00:00:42.141 align:start position:0%
accessibility of their websites,
testing the functionality--

00:00:42.174 --> 00:00:44.710 align:start size:97% position:3%
or testing the websites for
accessibility and advising the

00:00:44.743 --> 00:00:47.880
designers and developers on
how to fix issues he's found.

00:00:47.913 --> 00:00:51.451 align:start position:0%
He has written detailed training
courses on accessibility for

00:00:51.484 --> 00:00:54.687 align:start size:94% position:6%
developers which could
present on a regular basis.

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:57.356
He's also a WordPress developer
and has built many accessible

00:00:57.389 --> 00:01:00.793 align:start size:97% position:3%
WordPress websites for
clients, both large and small.

00:01:00.826 --> 00:01:04.163
He has contributed to the Make
WordPress Accessible Team and

00:01:04.196 --> 00:01:06.699 align:start size:94% position:6%
has spoken on accessibility
to many WordCamps

00:01:06.732 --> 00:01:08.634
and other WordPress meetups.

00:01:08.667 --> 00:01:11.838
Today he's going to be answering
the question, "So how do I know

00:01:11.871 --> 00:01:15.408 align:start size:88% position:13%
if my WordPress
website is accessible?"

00:01:15.441 --> 00:01:18.177
Graham, let's get started.

00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:19.612
Graham Armfield:
Okay, thanks a lot

00:01:19.645 --> 00:01:21.280
for the introduction, Allie.

00:01:21.313 --> 00:01:23.683
I'm gonna share my screen now.

00:01:23.716 --> 00:01:28.121 align:start size:84% position:16%
Can I share my screen?
Let's see.

00:01:28.154 --> 00:01:30.256 line:85%
Yeah, there we go.

00:01:30.289 --> 00:01:34.027 line:85%
Am I--yes, I am screen sharing.

00:01:34.894 --> 00:01:38.531 align:start size:81% position:19% line:83%
Thank you for the
introduction, Allie.

00:01:38.564 --> 00:01:40.666 line:85%
My name is Graham Armfield.

00:01:40.699 --> 00:01:44.670 line:83%
I'm just gonna make sure I have
the right screens visible on my

00:01:44.703 --> 00:01:47.673 line:83%
monitor here so that I
know what I'm doing.

00:01:47.706 --> 00:01:50.710 line:83%
Yeah, thank you for
the introduction.

00:01:50.743 --> 00:01:56.182 align:start position:0% line:83%
My talk, I'm honored to be doing
the first presentation

00:01:56.215 --> 00:02:00.119 align:start size:94% position:6% line:83%
at the first ever WordPress
Accessibility Day,

00:02:00.152 --> 00:02:02.755 align:start size:97% position:3% line:83%
and my presentation,
as Allie has said, is called,

00:02:02.788 --> 00:02:05.391 line:83%
"So How Do I Know If
My WordPress Website

00:02:05.424 --> 00:02:07.260 line:85%
Is Accessible?"

00:02:07.293 --> 00:02:09.028 line:85%
Okay, let's get going.

00:02:09.061 --> 00:02:10.830 line:85%
Now, a bit about me.

00:02:10.863 --> 00:02:13.399
Well, I don't really need to
introduce myself anymore 'cause

00:02:13.432 --> 00:02:15.168
Allie's already done it.

00:02:15.201 --> 00:02:19.605 align:start size:88% position:13%
Yes, I've been doing
accessibility for nearly

00:02:19.638 --> 00:02:21.374
20 years now.

00:02:21.407 --> 00:02:25.645
I started working on it for a
large financial, 20 years ago,

00:02:25.678 --> 00:02:28.114
and--but now I work on my own.

00:02:28.147 --> 00:02:31.217 align:start position:0%
My company is called Coolfields
Consulting, and yeah,

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:33.352 align:start size:81% position:19%
that's all I do now,
accessibility.

00:02:33.385 --> 00:02:38.224
I look at how websites are doing
on an accessibility scale, and I

00:02:38.257 --> 00:02:43.829
help developers understand the
problems and fix the problems as

00:02:43.862 --> 00:02:48.100 align:start position:0%
well, so there we go, and
I--yeah, I run training courses

00:02:48.133 --> 00:02:50.670
on a regular basis
with developers too.

00:02:50.703 --> 00:02:54.674 align:start position:0%
I've built a few accessible
WordPress sites over the years,

00:02:54.707 --> 00:02:59.178 align:start size:88% position:13%
and I can help people
build accessible themes.

00:02:59.211 --> 00:03:00.713
Right.

00:03:00.746 --> 00:03:05.117
Moving on, since mine's the
first talk, some of us--well,

00:03:05.150 --> 00:03:07.420
you know, everyone probably
knows what accessibility is,

00:03:07.453 --> 00:03:10.523
but I wanna talk a bit
about why it's important.

00:03:10.556 --> 00:03:13.025
Now, it affects more
people than you think.

00:03:13.058 --> 00:03:17.230 align:start position:0%
Something like 20% to 25% of
the population have some kind of

00:03:17.263 --> 00:03:22.134 align:start position:0%
different, perhaps, access
needs when it comes to websites.

00:03:22.167 --> 00:03:26.172
This might, of course, be caused
by blindness, poor vision, color

00:03:26.205 --> 00:03:31.577 align:start size:91% position:9%
blindness, dyslexia, ADHD,
autism, deafness,

00:03:31.610 --> 00:03:34.080
but also it's like, well,
people like my parents.

00:03:34.113 --> 00:03:36.148
They're just getting
older in their 80s now.

00:03:36.181 --> 00:03:38.584
They use the web every day.

00:03:38.617 --> 00:03:40.820 align:start size:97% position:3%
They need things to be simple,
and they need

00:03:40.853 --> 00:03:42.822
things to be clear.

00:03:42.855 --> 00:03:45.658
This picture that I'm showing
you, some of you may recognize

00:03:45.691 --> 00:03:47.493
it if you've been to London.

00:03:47.526 --> 00:03:50.329
It's the hill that leads up on
the northern side, the River

00:03:50.362 --> 00:03:55.768 align:start size:91% position:9%
Thames up to Saint Paul's
Cathedral here, okay?

00:03:55.801 --> 00:03:58.638
It crosses a couple of streets,
but it's just--it goes up the

00:03:58.671 --> 00:04:01.774
hill, and they've got steps
here for everyone to use.

00:04:01.807 --> 00:04:04.644 align:start size:97% position:3%
But they've also put this
ramp in when they built this.

00:04:04.677 --> 00:04:08.214
It's connected with the
millennium, so a few--

00:04:08.247 --> 00:04:10.016
20 years ago now.

00:04:10.049 --> 00:04:12.685 align:start position:0%
They put this ramp in here
presumably for wheelchair users

00:04:12.718 --> 00:04:19.058 align:start position:0%
and for, you know, for people
where, you know, we push chairs,

00:04:19.091 --> 00:04:22.528
buggies or whatever, but if you
stand here and look at people

00:04:22.561 --> 00:04:26.599
using this slope, you can see
that most people actually use

00:04:26.632 --> 00:04:29.135
the ramp rather than using
the stairs because perhaps

00:04:29.168 --> 00:04:30.670
they find it easier.

00:04:30.703 --> 00:04:34.140 line:83%
Now, it's one of the things
about doing accessibility is

00:04:34.173 --> 00:04:37.643 line:83%
that, without realizing that
you're doing it, accessibility,

00:04:37.676 --> 00:04:40.813 line:83%
doing things right, can help
everybody, not just the people,

00:04:40.846 --> 00:04:44.083 line:83%
the specific people
you're targeting.

00:04:44.116 --> 00:04:46.319
Okay, so what I'm
gonna cover, now,

00:04:46.352 --> 00:04:49.488 align:start size:84% position:16%
I'm familiar with the
WCAG guidelines.

00:04:49.521 --> 00:04:51.223
You may have heard of them.

00:04:51.256 --> 00:04:53.626
Officially, official title,
the Web Content Accessibility

00:04:53.659 --> 00:04:56.629 align:start size:88% position:13%
Guidelines, Version 2.1,
published by the Web

00:04:56.662 --> 00:04:59.699 align:start size:97% position:3%
Accessibility Initiative of
the World Wide Web Consortium.

00:04:59.732 --> 00:05:02.768
It's quiet a mouthful, and
there's a link there if you

00:05:02.801 --> 00:05:05.071
wanna find out more about them.

00:05:05.104 --> 00:05:08.774 align:start position:0% line:0%
Now, these are a great
resource for web accessibility.

00:05:08.807 --> 00:05:11.777 line:0%
There's lots of techniques in
there, things to do to test it,

00:05:11.810 --> 00:05:15.681 line:0%
but especially if you're new to
the game, it can be very hard

00:05:15.714 --> 00:05:17.717 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
to interpret what's
going on here.

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:20.286 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I still find bits that I'm not
really sure about, as well,

00:05:20.319 --> 00:05:22.788 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
when I say I've been doing it
for about 20 years now.

00:05:22.821 --> 00:05:28.561 align:start position:0% line:0%
So I thought, "Okay, what could
be useful would be a simple

00:05:28.594 --> 00:05:32.164 align:start size:94% position:6%
yes/no checklist for people,
and so that's what

00:05:32.197 --> 00:05:33.699
this presentation is.

00:05:33.732 --> 00:05:37.803 align:start position:0%
It's 15 questions, 15 simple
questions that you can ask about

00:05:37.836 --> 00:05:41.307
your own site, whether it's your
site or a site you're building

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:44.410
for a client or just any site
that you're looking at, things

00:05:44.443 --> 00:05:48.080
that you can check quite
easily about your sites

00:05:48.113 --> 00:05:49.648
and with free tools.

00:05:49.681 --> 00:05:51.817
I'll mention some of these, and
I've got some links at the end

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:56.188
on how to get hold of
those as well, okay?

00:05:56.221 --> 00:05:59.492
But in the short time that
I've got, I do not wanna

00:05:59.525 --> 00:06:01.093
talk for hours.

00:06:01.126 --> 00:06:02.628
I've got half an hour
to talk, and then we

00:06:02.661 --> 00:06:04.263
can do some questions.

00:06:04.296 --> 00:06:07.733
I can only cover some common
accessibility issues, but the

00:06:07.766 --> 00:06:11.036 align:start position:0%
ones I cover are ones that I
commonly find when I'm reviewing

00:06:11.069 --> 00:06:18.611 align:start position:0%
websites, and the--also, they're
sometimes the most important

00:06:18.644 --> 00:06:20.279
ones as well.

00:06:20.312 --> 00:06:22.214 align:start position:0%
So they're not--I'm not covering
everything, but if you can

00:06:22.247 --> 00:06:25.351 align:start position:0%
answer these questions
correctly, your site is gonna be

00:06:25.384 --> 00:06:27.620
a lot more accessible than
many websites out there.

00:06:27.653 --> 00:06:30.356
Sadly, there are a lot of
inaccessible websites,

00:06:30.389 --> 00:06:34.794 align:start position:0%
and the situation doesn't appear
to be getting any better.

00:06:34.827 --> 00:06:38.097
Firstly, we're gonna talk
about keyboard interaction.

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:41.066 align:start size:91% position:9%
And before we get onto the
actual questions itself

00:06:41.099 --> 00:06:44.403 align:start size:91% position:9%
why keyboard accessibility
is important.

00:06:44.436 --> 00:06:46.639 align:start size:94% position:6%
Well, some people
can't use a mouse, trackpad,

00:06:46.672 --> 00:06:49.175 align:start size:91% position:9%
or touch commands because
they perhaps have

00:06:49.208 --> 00:06:52.144 align:start size:88% position:13%
a motor impairment
that affects their hands

00:06:52.177 --> 00:06:54.346
or their arms, okay?

00:06:54.379 --> 00:06:57.216 align:start size:94% position:6%
So they're gonna potentially
be relying on keyboards

00:06:57.249 --> 00:06:59.351
to use their machines.

00:06:59.384 --> 00:07:01.720
Some people have very severe
motor impairments, and they'll

00:07:01.753 --> 00:07:05.758 align:start position:0%
be using switch devices, and
these hook into the keyboard API

00:07:05.791 --> 00:07:10.095 align:start size:94% position:6%
within their laptop or
their desktop machine, okay?

00:07:10.128 --> 00:07:12.731 align:start size:88% position:13%
So it's really important
that we get keyboard

00:07:12.764 --> 00:07:14.433
accessibility right.

00:07:14.466 --> 00:07:17.436
Also, if I'm using a screen
reader on my laptop here or a

00:07:17.469 --> 00:07:21.106
desktop machine, I'm gonna be
actually interacting with it

00:07:21.139 --> 00:07:24.109
using a series of keystrokes.

00:07:24.142 --> 00:07:26.145
So let's get on
to the questions.

00:07:26.178 --> 00:07:30.449 align:start position:0%
The first one, "Can I easily see
where keyboard focus is?",

00:07:30.482 --> 00:07:33.452 align:start size:91% position:9%
and the second one, "Can I
easily access all parts

00:07:33.485 --> 00:07:36.055
of the site using
just the keyboard?"

00:07:36.088 --> 00:07:38.791
Okay, the first one about
keyboard focus, if you're

00:07:38.824 --> 00:07:43.496 align:start size:94% position:6%
a mouse user, a touch user,
or you're using your--

00:07:43.529 --> 00:07:47.333
this, you know, a trackpad
underneath your keyboard,

00:07:47.366 --> 00:07:49.668 align:start size:94% position:6%
you're probably not gonna
have necessarily any concept

00:07:49.701 --> 00:07:51.403
of what a keyboard focus is,

00:07:51.436 --> 00:07:53.606 align:start size:91% position:9%
but if I'm a keyboard user
who's sighted,

00:07:53.639 --> 00:07:56.242 align:start size:81% position:19%
I will be relying on
it all the time.

00:07:56.275 --> 00:08:00.579 align:start size:97% position:3%
So if I'm gonna be tabbing
around a page to the links and

00:08:00.612 --> 00:08:04.383
other things that get focus, I
wanna know where keyword focus

00:08:04.416 --> 00:08:07.286 align:start size:84% position:16%
is 'cause it can
very easily get lost.

00:08:07.319 --> 00:08:09.455
So let's have a look at
this site, admittedly,

00:08:09.488 --> 00:08:11.323
not a WordPress site.

00:08:11.356 --> 00:08:15.227
Gov.uk is a well-known site in
the U.K., and it contains a vast

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:19.665 align:start size:97% position:3%
resource for everyone,
information about government,

00:08:19.698 --> 00:08:26.005 align:start position:0%
local governments, finance, tax,
disabled people, education,

00:08:26.038 --> 00:08:28.173
and what have you, and yes,
they've got a lot of stuff on

00:08:28.206 --> 00:08:33.145
coronavirus at the moment, and
it's won prizes, this design.

00:08:33.178 --> 00:08:36.749 align:start size:97% position:3%
If I hover over these links--I
hope you can see my mouse

00:08:36.782 --> 00:08:39.652 align:start position:0%
pointer here, but if I'm
hovering over one of those links

00:08:39.685 --> 00:08:42.288
at the moment, they do change
color, but it's quite a subtle

00:08:42.321 --> 00:08:44.590 align:start size:84% position:16%
change, but then with
my mouse pointer,

00:08:44.623 --> 00:08:46.792
I know where I am, okay?

00:08:46.825 --> 00:08:51.463 align:start size:94% position:6%
So if I'm a sighted keyboard
user, I'm gonna be really

00:08:51.496 --> 00:08:55.167
thankful for here, a very clear
indication of where keyboard

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.638 align:start position:0%
focus is, this yellow background
and black links, and that's

00:08:59.671 --> 00:09:01.774
common across the entire site.

00:09:01.807 --> 00:09:05.744 align:start size:84% position:16%
I can see at a
glance where focus is.

00:09:05.777 --> 00:09:07.413 line:0%
That's good.

00:09:07.446 --> 00:09:09.782 line:0%
Okay, actually, this is
a WordPress website,

00:09:09.815 --> 00:09:11.483 line:0%
Hassell Inclusion.

00:09:11.516 --> 00:09:15.087 line:0%
It's a company I do a lot of
work with, and here there is

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.756 line:0%
clear keyboard focus everywhere
on the site, and in terms of

00:09:17.789 --> 00:09:21.260 line:0%
getting to all the site, this is
good too because this navigation

00:09:21.293 --> 00:09:23.762 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
across the top, I've got
submenus hanging off some of

00:09:23.795 --> 00:09:27.600 line:0%
these elements, and I can get to
them with the keyboard as well,

00:09:27.633 --> 00:09:31.303 line:0%
so I think keyboard users are
not effectively locked out from

00:09:31.336 --> 00:09:35.174 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
the site as they
might be with this site.

00:09:35.207 --> 00:09:37.009
This is Odeon.

00:09:37.042 --> 00:09:41.046
In the U.K., this is a chain
of cinemas, and this is what

00:09:41.079 --> 00:09:43.782
happens when I hover
over this link here.

00:09:43.815 --> 00:09:46.452
I get this gray
hover indication,

00:09:46.485 --> 00:09:49.254
and this submenu appears.

00:09:49.287 --> 00:09:52.458
So that's going to show--you
know, I can choose from these

00:09:52.491 --> 00:09:54.259
things on here.

00:09:54.292 --> 00:09:57.129 line:0%
That's fine, but for keyboard
users, the situation is not so

00:09:57.162 --> 00:10:00.366 line:0%
great, because if I'm tabbing
through these navigation links,

00:10:00.399 --> 00:10:05.604 line:0%
I can't see at all where focus
is, and also, when I get--when I

00:10:05.637 --> 00:10:09.141 line:0%
actually get onto the "what's
on" link there, I'm not seeing

00:10:09.174 --> 00:10:12.411 line:0%
the submenu at all, and so it
can now be really difficult for

00:10:12.444 --> 00:10:15.514 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
keyboard users, and that could
include screen-reader users

00:10:15.547 --> 00:10:17.182 line:0%
here as well.

00:10:17.215 --> 00:10:19.485 align:start position:0% line:0%
It can actually be really
hard to find all the bits of the

00:10:19.518 --> 00:10:23.822 line:0%
sites, so that's
something to avoid.

00:10:23.855 --> 00:10:26.625
Let's have a look at a
couple more questions,

00:10:26.658 --> 00:10:30.496 align:start size:97% position:3%
and you need to answer yes
to both of these ones as well.

00:10:30.529 --> 00:10:34.400 align:start size:84% position:16%
"Does the keyboard
tab order Make sense?"

00:10:34.433 --> 00:10:37.836
and "Can I easily access all
the functionality of the site

00:10:37.869 --> 00:10:40.372
using the keyboard only?"

00:10:40.405 --> 00:10:43.609
The first, one tab order, that's
an easy one to check, assuming

00:10:43.642 --> 00:10:46.845 align:start position:0%
that you've got a visible focus,
or you can just press the tab

00:10:46.878 --> 00:10:50.749
key, and what you want is the
tab also to follow kind of the

00:10:50.782 --> 00:10:54.620 align:start size:97% position:3%
way that the pages are laid
out on the website that you're

00:10:54.653 --> 00:10:57.523
testing, whether it's yours
or somebody else's, okay?

00:10:57.556 --> 00:11:00.793
So you just need the tab order
to actually follow the content,

00:11:00.826 --> 00:11:05.297 align:start size:91% position:9%
really, ideally, and
not jump around randomly.

00:11:05.330 --> 00:11:07.833
But looking at the second
one, "Can I easily access

00:11:07.866 --> 00:11:10.269 align:start size:84% position:16%
all functionality with
the keyboard only?"

00:11:10.302 --> 00:11:11.770
Let's have a look at this.

00:11:11.803 --> 00:11:17.142 align:start position:0%
This is a WordPress site,
and it uses a "lightbox" plugin

00:11:17.175 --> 00:11:19.778 align:start size:81% position:19%
of which there are a
number available.

00:11:19.811 --> 00:11:23.482
Here, I've got these thumbnail
images in the content, and if I

00:11:23.515 --> 00:11:28.287
click on those images or tab to
them and press the enter key,

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:30.556
it actually shows me
a full-sized version

00:11:30.589 --> 00:11:32.725
of the image, okay?

00:11:32.758 --> 00:11:36.095 align:start size:91% position:9%
I'm sure you're all
familiar with the concept.

00:11:36.128 --> 00:11:38.630
The problem is, for keyboard
users, is that when I actually

00:11:38.663 --> 00:11:41.767 align:start position:0%
action that lightbox, yeah,
sure, I've got this nice picture

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:47.573 align:start position:0%
of the skyline in Newcastle upon
Tyne, as the sun is setting.

00:11:47.606 --> 00:11:52.611
That's great, but keyboard focus
has remained on the page below,

00:11:52.644 --> 00:11:54.880
so now I can't see
what's going on.

00:11:54.913 --> 00:11:57.516
If I press the tab key, I'm
actually moving through the

00:11:57.549 --> 00:12:00.619 align:start position:0%
underlying page, and I
can't get to the controls here.

00:12:00.652 --> 00:12:03.789
I can't close the
lightbox window.

00:12:03.822 --> 00:12:06.125 align:start size:94% position:6%
I can't get to these buttons
along the bottom,

00:12:06.158 --> 00:12:09.328
which takes me to the next or
the previous image on the page.

00:12:09.361 --> 00:12:12.064
So that's not great, okay?

00:12:12.097 --> 00:12:16.735
Jetpack, this is a WordPress
website, and they're generally

00:12:16.768 --> 00:12:19.238 align:start size:91% position:9%
not bad from an
accessibility perspective.

00:12:19.271 --> 00:12:21.440 align:start size:97% position:3%
They've got this language
selector here, so if I tab to

00:12:21.473 --> 00:12:26.278 align:start size:97% position:3%
the language selector and
press enter, I can see all the

00:12:26.311 --> 00:12:29.381 align:start size:91% position:9%
different options here
of the different languages

00:12:29.414 --> 00:12:33.418 align:start size:94% position:6%
that I can have this website
presented to me in.

00:12:33.451 --> 00:12:36.822
The problem here is, once again,
the keyboard focus actually is

00:12:36.855 --> 00:12:41.126
still on the underlying page,
and so it's now impossible for

00:12:41.159 --> 00:12:44.663 align:start position:0%
keyboard users and screen-reader
users to actually access

00:12:44.696 --> 00:12:47.266
and change the languages.

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:49.835
So that's a bit of a no-no.

00:12:49.868 --> 00:12:53.372 align:start size:91% position:9%
Okay, moving away from
talking about the keyboard

00:12:53.405 --> 00:12:57.743
accessibility, let's talk
about links in your pages.

00:12:57.776 --> 00:13:01.580 align:start size:94% position:6%
Okay, the first one, "Are
your links obviously links?"

00:13:01.613 --> 00:13:03.282
Do they look clickable?

00:13:03.315 --> 00:13:06.218 align:start size:97% position:3%
Can you tell them apart
from other things on the page?

00:13:06.251 --> 00:13:08.620 align:start size:78% position:22%
You need to answer
yes to that.

00:13:08.653 --> 00:13:14.626
Okay, this is a paragraph of
text about Exeter and Devon on

00:13:14.659 --> 00:13:19.131
a WordPress website, and this
particular theme, which sadly,

00:13:19.164 --> 00:13:23.302
quite a lot of themes do, they
have chosen by default to remove

00:13:23.335 --> 00:13:26.038 align:start size:88% position:13%
the underline from
all these links that are

00:13:26.071 --> 00:13:28.774
in this paragraph of content.

00:13:28.807 --> 00:13:30.342
There's a lot of links in there.

00:13:30.375 --> 00:13:32.110
You may or may not
be able to see them.

00:13:32.143 --> 00:13:34.179 align:start size:78% position:22%
They're marked out
in green text,

00:13:34.212 --> 00:13:36.148
assuming you're not color-blind.

00:13:36.181 --> 00:13:41.720 align:start position:0%
Okay, so it's a lot easier, even
if you have good vision, it's

00:13:41.753 --> 00:13:44.356
still quite easy--it's a lot
easier to see where these links

00:13:44.389 --> 00:13:47.659 align:start size:97% position:3%
are if, here, I've overwritten
the design to actually

00:13:47.692 --> 00:13:49.728
put the underlines back in.

00:13:49.761 --> 00:13:53.165
Now, I know some people don't
like these hard underlines,

00:13:53.198 --> 00:13:55.367 align:start size:81% position:19%
so you can use other
ways of doing it.

00:13:55.400 --> 00:14:00.205
You can use a gradient, or
the border, a bottom border,

00:14:00.238 --> 00:14:02.507
or something like that,
but please use this.

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:06.278
The underlines are like
a convention on the web

00:14:06.311 --> 00:14:08.247
to show where the links are.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.316
It's been around since the
dawn of the web, really.

00:14:11.349 --> 00:14:16.154
The other issue here with having
a few links in here with a green

00:14:16.187 --> 00:14:20.125 line:0%
with dark gray text is that
people who are colorblind or

00:14:20.158 --> 00:14:23.428 line:0%
have poor vision just may not be
able to see them at all because

00:14:23.461 --> 00:14:31.236 line:0%
they may just look very similar
to the actual plain content.

00:14:31.269 --> 00:14:32.771 line:0%
We can do better than that.

00:14:32.804 --> 00:14:35.340
Okay, so the next question--

00:14:35.373 --> 00:14:37.743 align:start size:91% position:9%
and you need to answer yes
to this one as well--

00:14:37.776 --> 00:14:40.712
"Do all the links provide
enough information to state

00:14:40.745 --> 00:14:42.347
where they lead to?"

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:44.383 align:start size:94% position:6%
Does it tell you where
the link is gonna take you?

00:14:44.416 --> 00:14:49.621
Okay, here, from a WordPress
site, are a couple of links.

00:14:49.654 --> 00:14:51.823 align:start size:94% position:6%
Now, sighted users are gonna
see immediately

00:14:51.856 --> 00:14:53.492
what's going on here.

00:14:53.525 --> 00:14:58.163
The first one, find out more
about my plugin and second,

00:14:58.196 --> 00:15:02.434 align:start position:0%
click here to read more
about our terms and conditions.

00:15:02.467 --> 00:15:06.071
But these links, whilst, for
sighted users, I can see what's

00:15:06.104 --> 00:15:10.676 align:start position:0%
going on, for screen-reader
users, the situation may not be

00:15:10.709 --> 00:15:15.480
as easy because an NVDA is a
screen reader that you can

00:15:15.513 --> 00:15:17.349
download for Windows machines.

00:15:17.382 --> 00:15:19.484 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's free to download, so
it's used by a lot of people.

00:15:19.517 --> 00:15:21.620 align:start size:81% position:19%
It's a very good
screen reader, okay?

00:15:21.653 --> 00:15:24.222 align:start size:97% position:3%
And it has these dialog boxes
which you can bring up

00:15:24.255 --> 00:15:26.258
called the elements list.

00:15:26.291 --> 00:15:28.126
You can see at the top there.

00:15:28.159 --> 00:15:32.164
And the links that we just
looked at are indicated here.

00:15:32.197 --> 00:15:34.599
Now, what this means is that
screen-reader users who are

00:15:34.632 --> 00:15:38.070
using this functionality--and
other screen readers carry this

00:15:38.103 --> 00:15:42.641 align:start size:97% position:3%
functionality as well--they're
not gonna get any context

00:15:42.674 --> 00:15:44.242
for these links.

00:15:44.275 --> 00:15:46.278 align:start position:0%
These links, presumably, each
one will take you to a different

00:15:46.311 --> 00:15:50.082 align:start position:0%
page, but as far as the
screen-reader user is concerned,

00:15:50.115 --> 00:15:51.416 align:start size:81% position:19%
they're just saying
click here,

00:15:51.449 --> 00:15:53.318 align:start size:81% position:19%
so that's not really
that informative.

00:15:53.351 --> 00:15:56.755 line:0%
The other thing to note about
the dialog boxes like this is

00:15:56.788 --> 00:16:01.059 align:start position:0% line:0%
that I can actually--if I--I can
choose one of these links and

00:16:01.092 --> 00:16:04.096 align:start position:0% line:0%
actually follow it directly from
here, so people are gonna be

00:16:04.129 --> 00:16:08.333 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
interacting with this elements
list rather than your pages

00:16:08.366 --> 00:16:11.803 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
directly if they're
using a screen reader.

00:16:11.836 --> 00:16:14.606 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
Now, with a small change
to the content, the situation

00:16:14.639 --> 00:16:16.441 line:0%
can be so much better.

00:16:16.474 --> 00:16:20.278 line:0%
Here, I've changed it to remove
the click heres and to put out

00:16:20.311 --> 00:16:23.515 line:0%
much more informative links, and
you'll see here in the elements

00:16:23.548 --> 00:16:27.319 line:0%
list that the screen reader is
now--screen-reader user is now

00:16:27.352 --> 00:16:31.223 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
gonna understand exactly where
it is that these links

00:16:31.256 --> 00:16:33.058 line:0%
are gonna take them.

00:16:33.091 --> 00:16:34.493 line:0%
So that's good.

00:16:34.526 --> 00:16:36.161 line:0%
And which version is easier?

00:16:36.194 --> 00:16:37.362 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
Well, the one on
the right-hand side.

00:16:37.395 --> 00:16:41.099 line:0%
So test your links to make
sure that they're meaningful.

00:16:41.132 --> 00:16:43.502 line:64%
We wanna avoid this.

00:16:43.535 --> 00:16:47.506 align:start position:0%
Now, if you've got--you got
blog on your WordPress website,

00:16:47.539 --> 00:16:51.043
you'll have a blog index page,
I'm sure, that you'll list your

00:16:51.076 --> 00:16:54.246 align:start size:88% position:13%
last 10 or 12 or however
many blog posts,

00:16:54.279 --> 00:16:57.616 align:start size:97% position:3%
and some themes could put
a lot of links into that page.

00:16:57.649 --> 00:17:01.586
And here, once again, I've got
the elements list from my screen

00:17:01.619 --> 00:17:06.291
reader, NVDA in this case,
and there's a lot of links.

00:17:06.324 --> 00:17:09.094 align:start size:97% position:3%
First one is--this is actually
the featured image for this

00:17:09.127 --> 00:17:13.065
post, and if I click on it, it
will take me to the blog post,

00:17:13.098 --> 00:17:16.768
but the link text here is
effectively Koala Bear.

00:17:16.801 --> 00:17:19.738 align:start size:97% position:3%
I'll talk a bit about featured
images in a moment.

00:17:19.771 --> 00:17:22.507 align:start size:97% position:3%
The actual blog post is called
ISTC Southern Area,

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:24.376
so that link is informative.

00:17:24.409 --> 00:17:27.446 align:start size:94% position:6%
I've also got links to
the date I published it on.

00:17:27.479 --> 00:17:30.582
If I'm not--you know, I'm not
publishing five blog posts

00:17:30.615 --> 00:17:34.219
a day, so it's not necessarily
that vital to have a link to

00:17:34.252 --> 00:17:36.588
that particular date.

00:17:36.621 --> 00:17:38.623 align:start size:97% position:3%
"Leave a comment," presumably
that's gonna take me

00:17:38.656 --> 00:17:42.127 align:start size:97% position:3%
to the bottom of the comments
on the comment section.

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:43.695
"Read more."

00:17:43.728 --> 00:17:47.799
Okay, now, if I got 10 or 12
links to blogs on this page,

00:17:47.832 --> 00:17:51.369
I'm gonna have multiple
links that say read more.

00:17:51.402 --> 00:17:53.171
Not very informative.

00:17:53.204 --> 00:17:56.374 align:start size:88% position:13%
I've got the categories
and the tags.

00:17:56.407 --> 00:17:59.211
So there's a lot going on here.

00:17:59.244 --> 00:18:01.246 align:start size:78% position:22%
Do these links
always make sense?

00:18:01.279 --> 00:18:02.714
I don't know.

00:18:02.747 --> 00:18:04.249
You--It's your decision, really.

00:18:04.282 --> 00:18:05.483
And this theme does a lot.

00:18:05.517 --> 00:18:08.053
Not all themes do as much as
that, and if you're building a

00:18:08.086 --> 00:18:12.491
theme for a client, think about
which ones are relevant here.

00:18:12.524 --> 00:18:17.762 align:start position:0%
Okay, moving away from
links, let's talk about images.

00:18:17.795 --> 00:18:20.699
And this first one, can
you answer yes to this?

00:18:20.732 --> 00:18:25.504
Do all the images on your pages
have appropriate alternate text?

00:18:25.537 --> 00:18:28.106 align:start size:91% position:9%
If I can't see the images
because I'm blind,

00:18:28.139 --> 00:18:32.811 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I will rely on alternate text,
using the alt attribute,

00:18:32.844 --> 00:18:36.214 line:0%
and yeah, in WordPress, it's
fairly easy to get this right

00:18:36.247 --> 00:18:37.816 line:0%
if you know what you're doing.

00:18:37.849 --> 00:18:39.618 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
This is another from
a WordPress site.

00:18:39.651 --> 00:18:42.787 line:0%
Here I'm using the Wave browser
extension, and I'll show you a

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:46.791 line:0%
link on where you can get that
from, and it shows me what the

00:18:46.824 --> 00:18:49.494 line:0%
alternate text is for all
the images on the page,

00:18:49.527 --> 00:18:51.229 line:0%
here Exeter Quayside.

00:18:51.262 --> 00:18:56.101 line:0%
Once again, Exeter is a city
in Devon in South West England.

00:18:56.134 --> 00:18:58.670 line:0%
I've got a green icon
here because it says--

00:18:58.703 --> 00:19:00.372 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
it's telling--you know,
it's saying,

00:19:00.405 --> 00:19:02.007 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
"Yeah, you've got
alternate text here."

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:03.408 line:0%
That's great.

00:19:03.441 --> 00:19:06.111 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
You get a red icon if
it's not set properly, okay?

00:19:06.144 --> 00:19:09.548 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
Now, the appropriate alternate
text may mean an empty alt

00:19:09.581 --> 00:19:13.518 line:0%
attributes, and if we have a
look at how you add images in

00:19:13.551 --> 00:19:17.289 align:start position:0%
the WordPress Classic
Editor, here is how you set the

00:19:17.322 --> 00:19:20.392 align:start position:0%
alternate text, and if you
notice underneath here, it says

00:19:20.425 --> 00:19:23.395 align:start size:94% position:6%
"leave empty if the image
is purely decorative," okay?

00:19:23.428 --> 00:19:27.499
So decorative images wanna end
up with an empty alt attribute,

00:19:27.532 --> 00:19:31.436
and this is a convention for
screen readers so that a screen

00:19:31.469 --> 00:19:33.672
reader comes across an
image that's got an empty

00:19:33.705 --> 00:19:35.774 align:start size:84% position:16%
alt attribute, then it
just ignores it.

00:19:35.807 --> 00:19:39.611 line:0%
It knows it's not really
anything meaningful there.

00:19:39.644 --> 00:19:43.348 line:0%
Just a note, if you're doing
this, make sure, if you set a

00:19:43.381 --> 00:19:46.718 line:0%
caption, it's a good idea to
set the alternate text as well,

00:19:46.751 --> 00:19:49.321 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
because not all screen readers
will actually link the two

00:19:49.354 --> 00:19:54.092 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
together even though
they're quite close on pages.

00:19:54.125 --> 00:19:57.462
And this is what it looks like
if you're doing it in Gutenberg,

00:19:57.495 --> 00:20:00.232
same sort of box.

00:20:00.265 --> 00:20:05.237 align:start size:97% position:3% line:76%
Okay, now where you've got
images that are part of links,

00:20:05.270 --> 00:20:08.473 line:76%
it's best to have the link
destination as the alternate

00:20:08.506 --> 00:20:12.577 align:start position:0% line:76%
text for that image, and in
this theme that I've used for my

00:20:12.610 --> 00:20:15.180 align:start size:88% position:13% line:76%
music site, that is the
case because if I--

00:20:15.213 --> 00:20:18.049 line:76%
this is the featured image
for this post, and this is

00:20:18.082 --> 00:20:20.218 line:78%
on my blog index page.

00:20:20.251 --> 00:20:22.254 align:start size:91% position:9% line:76%
If I click on that image,
it will take me

00:20:22.287 --> 00:20:25.824 line:76%
to the blog post called
"Recording Don't Let Go."

00:20:25.857 --> 00:20:27.659 line:78%
And you can have a look.

00:20:27.692 --> 00:20:30.161 line:76%
If you look under the bonnet at
the code, here's the link that

00:20:30.194 --> 00:20:33.331 align:start size:91% position:9% line:76%
takes me to the blog page,
the blog post,

00:20:33.364 --> 00:20:35.367 line:78%
and the alternate text.

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:39.337 line:76%
In the cases like this where the
image is part of the link, what

00:20:39.370 --> 00:20:43.475 align:start size:97% position:3% line:76%
the alt attribute is set to
becomes part of the link text.

00:20:43.508 --> 00:20:44.876 line:78%
So that's good.

00:20:44.909 --> 00:20:46.344 line:78%
This one's not so good.

00:20:46.377 --> 00:20:47.812 align:start size:84% position:16% line:76%
I showed you this
one a little earlier.

00:20:47.845 --> 00:20:54.519 align:start size:97% position:3% line:76%
Here's looking at the elements
list in NVDA screen reader.

00:20:54.552 --> 00:20:57.322 align:start position:0% line:76%
The actual clicking on the image
takes me to the blog post,

00:20:57.355 --> 00:21:00.558 line:76%
which is called ISTC
Southern Area, okay?

00:21:00.591 --> 00:21:04.162 line:76%
But the alternate text for
that image is Koala Bear,

00:21:04.195 --> 00:21:07.532 align:start size:97% position:3% line:76%
so a screen-reader user might
think that it takes me

00:21:07.565 --> 00:21:11.136 line:76%
to a story about koala
bears, but it doesn't.

00:21:11.169 --> 00:21:14.539 align:start size:94% position:6% line:76%
So if you're using a theme,
hopefully it's one

00:21:14.572 --> 00:21:16.675 line:78%
that doesn't do that.

00:21:16.708 --> 00:21:21.112 line:78%
Okay, videos now.

00:21:21.145 --> 00:21:22.681 align:start size:88% position:13% line:76%
This is an obvious one,
isn't it?

00:21:22.714 --> 00:21:24.816 align:start size:84% position:16% line:76%
"Do all your
videos have captions?"

00:21:24.849 --> 00:21:27.052 align:start position:0% line:76%
This is me doing this
presentation--it's not the first

00:21:27.085 --> 00:21:30.555 line:76%
time I've done it--to a group
of developers some time ago,

00:21:30.588 --> 00:21:32.557 line:0%
and it's on YouTube.

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:34.626 line:0%
So the captions are shown here.

00:21:34.659 --> 00:21:37.128 line:0%
I've made sure that the captions
are all up to date up, are right

00:21:37.161 --> 00:21:39.464 line:0%
and everything, up straight.

00:21:39.497 --> 00:21:43.168 align:start position:0% line:0%
Now, it's obviously deaf people
and people who are hard of

00:21:43.201 --> 00:21:46.404 align:start position:0% line:0%
hearing who rely on captions,
but actually, surveys have found

00:21:46.437 --> 00:21:50.075 align:start position:0% line:0%
out that many other people
can use captions with videos as

00:21:50.108 --> 00:21:54.546 align:start position:0% line:0%
well, sometimes people with
cognitive impairments, dyslexia,

00:21:54.579 --> 00:21:57.649 align:start position:0% line:0%
and other cognitive impairments,
will also use the captions

00:21:57.682 --> 00:22:01.119 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
as well 'cause it helps
underline what's being said.

00:22:01.152 --> 00:22:04.723 line:0%
Others, like, if you're watching
videos on Facebook or something

00:22:04.756 --> 00:22:08.326 line:0%
or in a crowded train or in an
office where you should be doing

00:22:08.359 --> 00:22:10.729 line:0%
something else, you might be
using the captions instead

00:22:10.762 --> 00:22:12.831 line:0%
of having it blaring out.

00:22:12.864 --> 00:22:17.235
Okay, so make sure your
videos have captions.

00:22:17.268 --> 00:22:20.839 align:start size:97% position:3%
Okay, a few questions
around what I like to call is

00:22:20.872 --> 00:22:25.744
signposting content, and the
first one, you need to answer

00:22:25.777 --> 00:22:29.647 align:start size:97% position:3%
yes to this: "Are your page
titles unique and meaningful?"

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:32.484
Now, actually, in WordPress,
it's pretty easy to get this

00:22:32.517 --> 00:22:35.420 align:start position:0%
right, because pretty much
every theme that I've ever come

00:22:35.453 --> 00:22:40.125
across will take whatever the
page title or the blog title is

00:22:40.158 --> 00:22:43.395
and actually use that as the
actual title element in the

00:22:43.428 --> 00:22:46.765 align:start size:94% position:6%
page, which is what you see
in this tab at the top

00:22:46.798 --> 00:22:48.633
of your browser, okay?

00:22:48.666 --> 00:22:52.504 align:start size:97% position:3%
So this is the one from
wordpress.org, and here's one

00:22:52.537 --> 00:22:56.074 align:start size:97% position:3%
from my own music site, okay,
the "Found My Way Album,"

00:22:56.107 --> 00:22:59.210 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
and if you look here,
it sets the title element

00:22:59.243 --> 00:23:02.213 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
to "Found My Way Album,"
Graham Armfield Music, right?

00:23:02.246 --> 00:23:05.250 align:start position:0% line:0%
The importance here is
that, when a screen-reader user

00:23:05.283 --> 00:23:09.621 align:start position:0% line:0%
arrives at a page for the first
time, the page title is the

00:23:09.654 --> 00:23:11.423 line:0%
first thing that they will hear.

00:23:11.456 --> 00:23:13.391 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
It helps people to know
that they're

00:23:13.424 --> 00:23:15.360 line:0%
in the right place, okay?

00:23:15.393 --> 00:23:18.396 line:0%
Sometimes I find websites that
just have the same page title

00:23:18.429 --> 00:23:23.668 line:0%
right across the board, so that
doesn't mean anything, really.

00:23:23.701 --> 00:23:25.804 align:start size:88% position:13%
Okay, the next question,
and yes, you need

00:23:25.837 --> 00:23:27.572
to answer yes to this one.

00:23:27.605 --> 00:23:30.775 align:start position:0%
"Do your pages have appropriate
headings and subheadings?"

00:23:30.808 --> 00:23:34.779
Now, headings used properly and
subheadings used properly help

00:23:34.812 --> 00:23:41.052 align:start size:97% position:3%
everybody, and here on my
Coolfield site, I've got some

00:23:41.085 --> 00:23:45.623 align:start position:0%
headings here, and I'm using the
Wave browser extension here,

00:23:45.656 --> 00:23:48.126 align:start size:94% position:6%
and not only does it show me
that there are headings,

00:23:48.159 --> 00:23:51.329 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
but it's also highlighting the
heading level as well

00:23:51.362 --> 00:23:53.665 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
because the heading levels are
important because they help

00:23:53.698 --> 00:23:56.501 line:0%
people get an idea
of what sections

00:23:56.534 --> 00:23:59.671 align:start size:78% position:22% line:0%
and subsections
within your pages,

00:23:59.704 --> 00:24:03.107
and how screen-reader users do
that is they'll use, once again,

00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:06.211 align:start size:97% position:3%
the elements list here, except
now, instead of looking

00:24:06.244 --> 00:24:08.379 align:start size:84% position:16%
at links, I'm looking
at headings.

00:24:08.412 --> 00:24:12.717
Notice that NVDA is exposing the
heading hierarchy, and when you

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:17.188
go through this list, the screen
reader will read out to you what

00:24:17.221 --> 00:24:20.625
heading is and what level it is
so people can try and build up

00:24:20.658 --> 00:24:26.297 align:start position:0%
a mental picture of the page
from the levels of the headings,

00:24:26.330 --> 00:24:30.802 line:0%
so make sure that yours
are set appropriately.

00:24:30.835 --> 00:24:34.205 align:start position:0% line:0%
The important thing to note here
is that headings in NVDA and

00:24:34.238 --> 00:24:37.675 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
other screen readers have
functionality similar to this.

00:24:37.708 --> 00:24:41.312 line:0%
You can use these things to
jump around the page, okay?

00:24:41.345 --> 00:24:43.181 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
So if I find a heading
I'm interested in,

00:24:43.214 --> 00:24:47.852 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
press the enter key,
it takes me straight to it.

00:24:47.885 --> 00:24:51.756 align:start size:91% position:9%
Okay, talking about people
jumping around pages,

00:24:51.789 --> 00:24:54.492
"Are all your landmarks
being used correctly?"

00:24:54.525 --> 00:24:57.662 align:start size:94% position:6%
Now, when I've done other
presentations to developers,

00:24:57.695 --> 00:25:00.732 align:start size:97% position:3%
actually, I'm finding that not
very many developers know

00:25:00.765 --> 00:25:03.535
what landmarks are.

00:25:03.568 --> 00:25:08.606
But actually, many people do
use them without realizing.

00:25:08.639 --> 00:25:12.277 align:start position:0%
Landmarks, they're
predefined areas within a page.

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:16.781
This is a typical--but not--it's
not the only design for a site.

00:25:16.814 --> 00:25:19.350 align:start size:91% position:9%
I've got a banner at
the top, some navigation.

00:25:19.383 --> 00:25:23.187 align:start size:94% position:6%
My main content and a footer
and a sidebar here, okay?

00:25:23.220 --> 00:25:27.725 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
It's sort of an older style
layout for a page.

00:25:27.758 --> 00:25:31.729 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
Okay, now, screen-reader users
may use these landmarks

00:25:31.762 --> 00:25:34.499 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
to jump around to find a bit
they're interested in.

00:25:34.532 --> 00:25:37.468 align:start position:0% line:0%
The key thing here is when I
arrive at a new page, it's often

00:25:37.501 --> 00:25:40.638 line:0%
the main content of that page is
the bit that I'm most interested

00:25:40.671 --> 00:25:46.644 line:0%
in, and so I wanna try and find
the main content landmark, okay?

00:25:46.677 --> 00:25:48.780 line:0%
And then when I've read that,
then I might wanna find the

00:25:48.813 --> 00:25:52.350 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
navigation to go and find
something else on your site.

00:25:52.383 --> 00:25:58.489
Now, most developers don't use
landmarks on purpose, but they

00:25:58.522 --> 00:26:04.228
probably are using the HTML5
elements like these, okay?

00:26:04.261 --> 00:26:08.232 align:start size:97% position:3%
And if you use them properly,
they set up landmarks

00:26:08.265 --> 00:26:10.535
in an appropriate way.

00:26:10.568 --> 00:26:14.105
So make sure you are using them
properly because screen-reader

00:26:14.138 --> 00:26:17.075
users will be using them.

00:26:17.108 --> 00:26:19.077 align:start size:88% position:13%
Okay, so how do you
test for the landmarks?

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:22.246
Well, there's a browser
extension for that too.

00:26:22.279 --> 00:26:25.149 align:start position:0%
It's one that's called Landmark
Navigation via Keyboard

00:26:25.182 --> 00:26:26.584
or Pop-up.

00:26:26.617 --> 00:26:27.852 line:0%
It's available for Firefox.

00:26:27.885 --> 00:26:30.588 line:0%
As you can see here, I've got
Firefox in the screenshot, or

00:26:30.621 --> 00:26:35.460 line:0%
it's also on Chrome as well,
and if you check this box here,

00:26:35.493 --> 00:26:39.063 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
show all landmarks, it puts
these outlines on your page so

00:26:39.096 --> 00:26:43.434 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
you can see where all the
landmarks on your pages are.

00:26:43.467 --> 00:26:46.404 line:0%
The key thing that's missing
from this page, because this

00:26:46.437 --> 00:26:49.707 align:start position:0% line:0%
theme, this WordPress theme
didn't put them there, there is

00:26:49.740 --> 00:26:53.845 line:0%
no main landmark, so it's no
way using landmarks over a

00:26:53.878 --> 00:26:56.681 line:0%
screen-reader user jumping
straight to the main content

00:26:56.714 --> 00:26:58.416 line:0%
of the page, okay?

00:26:58.449 --> 00:27:00.618 align:start position:0% line:0%
There might be other ways of
doing it, but if I'm a landmarks

00:27:00.651 --> 00:27:05.757 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
user, then it's not
easy for me to get there.

00:27:05.790 --> 00:27:10.194
Okay, next one, looking at text.

00:27:10.227 --> 00:27:13.031
"Can I resize text in a page
without breaking the layout?"

00:27:13.064 --> 00:27:15.299 align:start size:84% position:16%
Obviously, you need
to answer yes to that.

00:27:15.332 --> 00:27:17.802
Okay, here's some--a list
of links, a normal size.

00:27:17.835 --> 00:27:20.038 align:start size:84% position:16%
I took this screenshot
a few years ago,

00:27:20.071 --> 00:27:23.441 align:start size:97% position:3%
but it illustrates the problem
I find well--

00:27:23.474 --> 00:27:25.543
I find on some websites.

00:27:25.576 --> 00:27:27.812 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
So here's normal text size,
and this is what it looks like

00:27:27.845 --> 00:27:29.580 line:0%
when I made the text bigger.

00:27:29.613 --> 00:27:33.484 line:0%
It's important to realize that
zooming and text resizing are

00:27:33.517 --> 00:27:35.653 line:0%
not the same thing in browsers.

00:27:35.686 --> 00:27:39.724 line:0%
Zooming is the default option,
but people do use text resizing,

00:27:39.757 --> 00:27:43.428 line:0%
if they got poor vision,
to make things bigger.

00:27:43.461 --> 00:27:46.631 line:0%
And you know, people do that,
so it's important that you test

00:27:46.664 --> 00:27:50.368 line:0%
your site to make sure
that it can cope with it.

00:27:50.401 --> 00:27:52.270 line:0%
This didn't.

00:27:52.303 --> 00:27:54.238 line:0%
And it's quite easy to find
other examples across the

00:27:54.271 --> 00:27:59.477 line:0%
Internet, where resizing
kind of breaks sites badly.

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:02.747 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
Hopefully, it doesn't
break your site.

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:06.484 line:0%
Next one, "Are you using
fully justified text?"

00:28:06.517 --> 00:28:09.353
And I would hope that
you're not, really.

00:28:09.386 --> 00:28:13.591
So here's a paragraph of text,
left aligned, and this is what

00:28:13.624 --> 00:28:16.160
it looks like when
it's fully justified.

00:28:16.193 --> 00:28:19.197 align:start position:0%
What the browser is doing
here is it's stretching the gaps

00:28:19.230 --> 00:28:20.765
between the words.

00:28:20.798 --> 00:28:22.533
So, for example,
on this line here,

00:28:22.566 --> 00:28:24.435 align:start size:91% position:9%
"Cathedral founded
in the mid-11th century,"

00:28:24.468 --> 00:28:27.271 align:start size:84% position:16%
it's had to stretch
the words quite a long

00:28:27.304 --> 00:28:30.007 align:start size:94% position:6%
way apart, much
further than on other lines.

00:28:30.040 --> 00:28:34.779
Now, this actually creates a
cognitive load for everybody

00:28:34.812 --> 00:28:39.150 line:0%
but especially so for
some dyslexic people.

00:28:39.183 --> 00:28:41.619 line:0%
There is around 8% to 10%
of the population could be

00:28:41.652 --> 00:28:43.454 line:0%
affected by this.

00:28:43.487 --> 00:28:45.356 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
You get this rivers
of white space effect.

00:28:45.389 --> 00:28:49.327 line:0%
I have a friend who's severely
dyslexic, and she couldn't read

00:28:49.360 --> 00:28:52.396 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
this paragraph if
it's fully justified.

00:28:52.429 --> 00:28:54.365 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
She just could
not read it at all.

00:28:54.398 --> 00:28:57.535 align:start size:78% position:22% line:0%
The spaces just
tend to take over.

00:28:58.736 --> 00:29:01.773
Okay, a question around forms.

00:29:01.806 --> 00:29:04.308
In my forms, "Do all
the form fields have

00:29:04.341 --> 00:29:06.577
an accompanying label?"

00:29:06.610 --> 00:29:10.181
They need to for screen-reader
users, really, because the way

00:29:10.214 --> 00:29:14.285
that screen readers work, when I
arrive at this input field here,

00:29:14.318 --> 00:29:17.555
I need to find out what it's
for, so the properly marked-up

00:29:17.588 --> 00:29:20.525 align:start size:88% position:13%
labels are vital here
for screen-reader users.

00:29:20.558 --> 00:29:24.395 align:start position:0%
This is--I'm using the Wave
add-on here, and it's showing me

00:29:24.428 --> 00:29:27.765
that all these labels are
properly marked up so that

00:29:27.798 --> 00:29:30.334 align:start size:94% position:6%
a screen-reader user should
have no problems using

00:29:30.367 --> 00:29:32.103
this form, okay?

00:29:32.136 --> 00:29:35.439 align:start size:91% position:9%
However, on this website,
WordPress website,

00:29:35.472 --> 00:29:37.408
using the Contact Form 7,

00:29:37.441 --> 00:29:40.645 align:start size:91% position:9%
with the default settings,
sadly, the labels,

00:29:40.678 --> 00:29:44.048
what looks like a label here, is
not linked to the input field,

00:29:44.081 --> 00:29:46.617
so screen readers
will struggle here.

00:29:46.650 --> 00:29:49.687 align:start position:0%
So have a look at your own forms
and see what happens

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:53.291
with the Wave tool.

00:29:54.158 --> 00:29:59.630
Okay, the last question,
"Is the color contrast

00:29:59.663 --> 00:30:01.465
on your pages sufficient?"

00:30:01.498 --> 00:30:04.569 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
Obviously, you need
to answer yes.

00:30:04.602 --> 00:30:09.240 line:0%
What we want to avoid is people
not being able to read the text

00:30:09.273 --> 00:30:13.578 align:start position:0% line:0%
because it's like a dark gray on
a lightweight gray background

00:30:13.611 --> 00:30:15.279 line:0%
or something like that.

00:30:15.312 --> 00:30:18.482 align:start position:0% line:0%
There are rules about what
the color contrast needs to be.

00:30:18.515 --> 00:30:21.118 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
To test it, you could use this
tool, and I'll put the link

00:30:21.151 --> 00:30:23.154
a bit later on, so
you can download it.

00:30:23.187 --> 00:30:27.458
It's for Windows machines and
Macs as well, and you could use

00:30:27.491 --> 00:30:30.761 align:start position:0%
these color picker elements here
and actually use this,

00:30:30.794 --> 00:30:34.799
and it will tell you immediately
whether it passes or fails the

00:30:34.832 --> 00:30:38.069
WCAG 2.1 guidelines, okay?

00:30:38.102 --> 00:30:41.806 align:start position:0%
And quite a lot of these blue
on the white backgrounds on this

00:30:41.839 --> 00:30:44.342
particular website failed.

00:30:44.375 --> 00:30:47.845
This is a site I looked
at a couple of years ago.

00:30:47.878 --> 00:30:49.714
Okay, here's another one.

00:30:49.747 --> 00:30:51.515
You've seen this a bit before.

00:30:51.548 --> 00:30:54.185 align:start size:84% position:16%
Okay, these text
links here are green.

00:30:54.218 --> 00:30:57.288 align:start position:0%
The problem is this green has
not--insufficient color contrast

00:30:57.321 --> 00:31:00.458 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
against the white,
and so it will show up.

00:31:00.491 --> 00:31:03.327 line:0%
And now, here, I'm using
the aXe browser extension.

00:31:03.360 --> 00:31:05.763 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
This is another
useful accessibility tool.

00:31:05.796 --> 00:31:08.532 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
The link will be
provided very shortly.

00:31:08.565 --> 00:31:12.136 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
And the great thing
about aXe is it groups

00:31:12.169 --> 00:31:14.405 line:0%
all the errors together.

00:31:14.438 --> 00:31:19.243 line:0%
So here I've got 53 elements on
this page that have insufficient

00:31:19.276 --> 00:31:21.746 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
color contrast,
and it's literally all

00:31:21.779 --> 00:31:24.382 line:0%
these green links, okay?

00:31:24.415 --> 00:31:27.084 line:0%
And you can highlight them as
well on the page so you can see

00:31:27.117 --> 00:31:28.653 line:0%
exactly what it's talking about.

00:31:28.686 --> 00:31:30.488 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
It gives you some
ideas about how to fix it.

00:31:30.521 --> 00:31:33.224 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I can actually scroll through
all the 53 of those

00:31:33.257 --> 00:31:35.226 line:0%
if I want to.

00:31:35.259 --> 00:31:39.197 line:0%
Okay, there we go.

00:31:39.864 --> 00:31:43.334 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
So there are 15
questions, hopefully,

00:31:43.367 --> 00:31:46.304 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
fairly straightforward
to look at, using the tools

00:31:46.337 --> 00:31:48.072 line:0%
that I've mentioned.

00:31:48.105 --> 00:31:50.408 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
Okay, you got browser
tools in there, like as I--

00:31:50.441 --> 00:31:52.510 line:0%
just tabbing around a page.

00:31:52.543 --> 00:31:54.445 line:0%
I've got the Colour
Contrast Analyzer.

00:31:54.478 --> 00:31:57.682 line:0%
This is not a browser extension,
but it's available for Windows

00:31:57.715 --> 00:32:00.484 line:0%
machines and Macs.

00:32:00.517 --> 00:32:04.722 align:start position:0% line:0%
Paciello Group, American
company, accessibility company.

00:32:04.755 --> 00:32:08.125 line:0%
Then the Wave testing
tool is made by WebAIM.

00:32:08.158 --> 00:32:10.628 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
That's another
accessibility company.

00:32:10.661 --> 00:32:12.797 line:0%
It's available for
Chrome and Firefox.

00:32:12.830 --> 00:32:17.101 line:0%
And then aXe is made by Deque,
and that's available for Chrome,

00:32:17.134 --> 00:32:18.703 line:0%
Firefox, and Edge.

00:32:18.736 --> 00:32:21.672 align:start position:0% line:0%
And these tools, I use them
all the time when I'm reviewing

00:32:21.705 --> 00:32:24.809 line:0%
websites for accessibility.

00:32:24.842 --> 00:32:30.481 line:0%
I've also written some stuff
about accessibility myself.

00:32:30.514 --> 00:32:33.184 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
Here are--I wrote--
I was amazed.

00:32:33.217 --> 00:32:36.087 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
I actually wrote this or
published this blog post ten

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:39.857 align:start position:0% line:0%
years ago now, but still, I'm
finding websites that don't have

00:32:39.890 --> 00:32:43.561 line:0%
alternate text set correctly, so
if you're not sure, go and have

00:32:43.594 --> 00:32:46.230 line:0%
a look at this blog post,
and it gives you some ideas

00:32:46.263 --> 00:32:50.234 line:0%
of how to do it properly
in each of many situations.

00:32:50.267 --> 00:32:54.338 align:start position:0% line:0%
Okay, if you're at all wondering
about how to mark up forms

00:32:54.371 --> 00:32:56.707 align:start size:94% position:6% line:0%
for accessibility, I've got
a series of blog posts

00:32:56.740 --> 00:32:58.442 line:0%
about that as well.

00:32:58.475 --> 00:33:00.111 line:0%
You can find them here.

00:33:00.144 --> 00:33:02.580 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
And then as a technique
that I described--

00:33:02.613 --> 00:33:04.348 line:0%
I didn't invent it by any means,

00:33:04.381 --> 00:33:06.283 align:start size:78% position:22% line:0%
but I describe how
to do it here,

00:33:06.316 --> 00:33:08.619 line:0%
"Text for screen readers only."

00:33:08.652 --> 00:33:10.221 line:0%
So it's some text.

00:33:10.254 --> 00:33:12.056 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
You can put some extra
information text there for

00:33:12.089 --> 00:33:16.660 line:0%
screen-reader users, but it's
not visible for sighted users,

00:33:16.693 --> 00:33:19.730 line:0%
so there's a bit about that too.

00:33:19.763 --> 00:33:23.667 align:start position:0% line:0%
Okay, things I didn't cover, and
so I just didn't have time to

00:33:23.700 --> 00:33:27.671 line:0%
cover in here, like other things
as well, so you know, there are

00:33:27.704 --> 00:33:31.409 align:start position:0% line:0%
all kind of accessibility,
all kind of tests around all of

00:33:31.442 --> 00:33:34.745 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
these things, but you know,
the ones I showed are probably

00:33:34.778 --> 00:33:37.415 line:0%
the most important.

00:33:37.448 --> 00:33:39.083 line:92%
And there we go.

00:33:39.116 --> 00:33:41.685 line:91%
That's the end of
my presentation.

00:33:41.718 --> 00:33:45.656 align:start size:94% position:6% line:91%
Hope you found it
interesting and informative.

00:33:51.862 --> 00:33:53.364 line:92%
Allie: Wonderful.

00:33:53.397 --> 00:33:55.066 line:92%
Graham, thank you so much.

00:33:55.099 --> 00:33:57.735 line:91%
We are gonna go ahead and
go through some questions.

00:33:57.768 --> 00:33:59.470 line:92%
Graham: Excellent.

00:33:59.503 --> 00:34:01.539 align:start size:91% position:9%
Allie: The first one that
I'm seeing here asks,

00:34:01.572 --> 00:34:05.309
"Is image captioning also
a part of accessibility?"

00:34:05.342 --> 00:34:06.811
Graham: Image captioning.

00:34:06.844 --> 00:34:11.415
Okay, so that's an interesting
one, because yes, in WordPress

00:34:11.448 --> 00:34:14.518
sites, you can set the alternate
text for an image when you add

00:34:14.551 --> 00:34:18.756
it to a page or a post, and
you can set a caption too.

00:34:18.789 --> 00:34:26.530
Now, in newer WordPress themes,
what it does under the bonnet,

00:34:26.563 --> 00:34:29.300
so I'm not sure where everyone's
gonna be as a developer on this

00:34:29.333 --> 00:34:34.105 align:start position:0%
particular call, so I am
gonna get a bit technical here.

00:34:34.138 --> 00:34:38.209 align:start position:0%
It actually puts the image
and the caption in a figure and

00:34:38.242 --> 00:34:42.046
marks up the caption with a
fake caption, okay, which is

00:34:42.079 --> 00:34:47.351 align:start position:0%
a--I think it's a relatively
new--perhaps an HTML5 construct.

00:34:47.384 --> 00:34:51.856 align:start position:0%
Some screen readers do actually
now link these two things

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:54.825
together, but I wrote a blog
post about this a couple of

00:34:54.858 --> 00:34:59.697
years ago, and it's
not consistent--

00:34:59.730 --> 00:35:03.300 align:start size:97% position:3%
it's not consistently
implemented in screen readers,

00:35:03.333 --> 00:35:06.203 align:start size:88% position:13%
so at the moment, that's
why I recommended it

00:35:06.236 --> 00:35:10.241
when you're adding an image
into a blog post or a page.

00:35:10.274 --> 00:35:13.277
It's--even if you're setting
the caption, it's a good idea

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:17.481 align:start position:0%
to set--still set the alternate
text as well because

00:35:17.514 --> 00:35:21.652 align:start size:94% position:6%
some screen readers will not
link the two together.

00:35:21.685 --> 00:35:23.521 align:start size:72% position:28%
Allie: Got it.
Wonderful.

00:35:23.554 --> 00:35:26.290 align:start size:94% position:6%
Next question, "You've been
working in the business

00:35:26.323 --> 00:35:28.025
for over 20 years.

00:35:28.058 --> 00:35:31.295 align:start position:0%
What has been the most important
advance in web or WordPress

00:35:31.328 --> 00:35:33.731 align:start size:78% position:22%
accessibility
during that time?"

00:35:33.764 --> 00:35:38.335
Graham: Okay, well,
it's interesting.

00:35:38.368 --> 00:35:42.439 align:start size:97% position:3%
HTML5 actually, which started
to appear--I mean,

00:35:42.472 --> 00:35:44.642 align:start position:0%
I think that it's published--the
specification was published

00:35:44.675 --> 00:35:47.511 align:start size:81% position:19%
12 years ago or
something like that.

00:35:47.544 --> 00:35:52.650
Over the last few years, more
recently, support for HTML5

00:35:52.683 --> 00:35:57.488
elements has been getting better
all the time, and I mentioned,

00:35:57.521 --> 00:36:01.659 align:start position:0%
when I was talking about
landmarks, that the HTML sites'

00:36:01.692 --> 00:36:06.397
sectioning elements, sectioning
elements like main, nav, header,

00:36:06.430 --> 00:36:11.635
footer, et cetera, they have
really helped because now they

00:36:11.668 --> 00:36:16.173 align:start size:97% position:3%
can define regions within
pages for screen-reader users.

00:36:16.206 --> 00:36:20.444 align:start position:0%
Unfortunately, some of the other
great things that HTML5 has

00:36:20.477 --> 00:36:25.616
introduced, like, for example,
"input type equals dates," which

00:36:25.649 --> 00:36:30.788
gives you a fully--or in theory
gives you a fully accessible

00:36:30.821 --> 00:36:38.229
date entry field for your forms,
it works in some browsers, and

00:36:38.262 --> 00:36:42.533 align:start position:0%
it works in some screen readers,
but it's not at all supported

00:36:42.566 --> 00:36:46.370
by IE 11, Internet Explorer 11,
which perhaps might--wouldn't

00:36:46.403 --> 00:36:54.211
surprise you, but even Safari on
Macs doesn't support input type

00:36:54.244 --> 00:36:56.480 align:start size:97% position:3%
equals date, and there's been
an outstanding bug about

00:36:56.513 --> 00:36:58.148
that for many, many years.

00:36:58.181 --> 00:37:01.218
I think Apple need to get their
backsides in gear and actually

00:37:01.251 --> 00:37:05.155
support--start supporting that,
because let's face it--I didn't

00:37:05.188 --> 00:37:08.993 align:start position:0%
mention date pickers during
the presentation, but if you're

00:37:09.026 --> 00:37:11.795
providing a date picker for
somebody to use, it can be

00:37:11.828 --> 00:37:15.399
a hell of an experience if
it's not an accessible one,

00:37:15.432 --> 00:37:17.701 align:start size:94% position:6%
especially if you force
people to use a date picker.

00:37:17.734 --> 00:37:19.370
That's not a good idea at all.

00:37:19.403 --> 00:37:22.339
So I think, overall, to
summarize, HTML5 elements

00:37:22.372 --> 00:37:26.377 align:start size:97% position:3%
have started to make a real
difference now, and as support

00:37:26.410 --> 00:37:30.381
for these elements in browsers
and screen readers increases,

00:37:30.414 --> 00:37:32.783 align:start size:84% position:16%
then it's, you know--
because you know,

00:37:32.816 --> 00:37:34.451
who wouldn't wanna use them?

00:37:34.484 --> 00:37:36.053 align:start size:84% position:16%
Because you get a
lot of stuff for free.

00:37:36.086 --> 00:37:39.490 align:start size:97% position:3%
Whenever you use native
HTML elements, you get all the

00:37:39.523 --> 00:37:44.194
accessibility for free there,
so let's start using them once

00:37:44.227 --> 00:37:46.530
they're well supported.

00:37:46.563 --> 00:37:48.599 align:start size:78% position:22%
Allie: Beautiful.
Great answer.

00:37:48.632 --> 00:37:52.569
Next question is "Which
colors are best to use

00:37:52.602 --> 00:37:54.505
in accessible design?"

00:37:54.538 --> 00:37:57.107 align:start size:91% position:9%
I feel like that might
have a complicated answer.

00:37:57.140 --> 00:38:00.444 align:start size:94% position:6%
Graham: Well, yeah,
I'll try and keep it short.

00:38:00.477 --> 00:38:04.014
Okay, so that's an
interesting one.

00:38:04.047 --> 00:38:08.519
And talking about color contrast
is, as I did earlier, obviously,

00:38:08.552 --> 00:38:14.258
the most color contrast could be
provided by having black text on

00:38:14.291 --> 00:38:18.395
a white background, but I would
caution against that because

00:38:18.428 --> 00:38:23.500
whilst that's the maximum color
contrast you could ever have,

00:38:23.533 --> 00:38:25.669
this is not good
for some Dyslexics.

00:38:25.702 --> 00:38:28.372
Some people who are dyslexic
will find that that's just

00:38:28.405 --> 00:38:30.341
too much color contrast.

00:38:30.374 --> 00:38:33.744
It's too in your face, which
is another colloquial term,

00:38:33.777 --> 00:38:36.246 align:start size:91% position:9%
but hopefully everyone
knows what I mean by that.

00:38:36.279 --> 00:38:42.086
So I think, don't--yeah,
avoid maybe black on white,

00:38:42.119 --> 00:38:43.787
or white on black.

00:38:43.820 --> 00:38:45.289
These are quite good.

00:38:45.322 --> 00:38:47.091 align:start size:81% position:19%
Maybe high-contrast,
you know,

00:38:47.124 --> 00:38:49.360
schemes are good
for some people.

00:38:49.393 --> 00:38:52.629 align:start size:97% position:3%
Just, I mean, most people
who--most organizations I work

00:38:52.662 --> 00:38:56.300
with, they already got a brand
palette already, and a lot of

00:38:56.333 --> 00:39:00.571
organizations have color colors
in their brand palette that will

00:39:00.604 --> 00:39:05.442 align:start size:97% position:3%
actually provide combinations
that provide enough color

00:39:05.475 --> 00:39:07.378
contrast without being too much.

00:39:07.411 --> 00:39:11.315
Some organizations, that's not
true, and then it can be a real

00:39:11.348 --> 00:39:12.583
problem with them.

00:39:12.616 --> 00:39:16.420
So I think just make sure that
you get enough color contrast

00:39:16.453 --> 00:39:19.456
there and using the tool
that I mentioned earlier.

00:39:19.489 --> 00:39:22.192 align:start size:88% position:13%
Either aXe, or the
Colour Contrast Analyzer

00:39:22.225 --> 00:39:24.061
will help you there.

00:39:24.094 --> 00:39:27.431
Try and avoid, like, blacks
and white--black and white.

00:39:27.464 --> 00:39:30.267 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's a bit too
much for some people.

00:39:30.300 --> 00:39:33.070
Allie: So it sounds like the
summary of that is it's maybe

00:39:33.103 --> 00:39:36.140 align:start position:0%
less about the color themselves,
but the relationship between

00:39:36.173 --> 00:39:38.809 align:start position:0%
the color, like, how the colors
contrast with each other.

00:39:38.842 --> 00:39:42.780 align:start size:75% position:25%
Graham: Yeah,
yeah, that's it.

00:39:42.813 --> 00:39:46.116 align:start size:94% position:6%
Allie: So the next question,
"Do you have a go-to or

00:39:46.149 --> 00:39:48.685 align:start size:84% position:16%
recommended theme
that is ally-friendly

00:39:48.718 --> 00:39:51.555
as a starting point?

00:39:51.588 --> 00:39:53.157
Graham: That's
a good question.

00:39:53.190 --> 00:39:57.661 align:start size:94% position:6%
When I've been--when I
built WordPress websites for

00:39:57.694 --> 00:40:00.397
organizations--over the last
ten years, I've been doing

00:40:00.430 --> 00:40:05.369
that--literally, I have always
started from scratch and built

00:40:05.402 --> 00:40:09.173
my own, and I've got my own,
like, effectively, starter

00:40:09.206 --> 00:40:11.575 align:start size:81% position:19%
theme, which I
tend to just tweak.

00:40:11.608 --> 00:40:13.811
I think many developers
work that way anyway.

00:40:13.844 --> 00:40:20.717 align:start position:0%
But that said, a lot of the
defaults, WordPress themes, are

00:40:20.750 --> 00:40:25.122
pretty good, like the 20x, 2020,
2019, and everything like that.

00:40:25.155 --> 00:40:27.825 align:start size:88% position:13%
I believe their
features are quite good.

00:40:27.858 --> 00:40:32.062 align:start position:0%
I don't have a name of any other
themes that I can recommend.

00:40:32.095 --> 00:40:36.266
Things to look out for, though,
within the theme review process,

00:40:36.299 --> 00:40:42.206
there is a tag that people can
apply for, theme developers can

00:40:42.239 --> 00:40:44.875 align:start size:81% position:19%
apply for, called
accessibility ready.

00:40:44.908 --> 00:40:47.845 align:start position:0%
It was something that was
introduced by the accessibility

00:40:47.878 --> 00:40:51.548
team, and Joe did a lot of
work on this over the years,

00:40:51.581 --> 00:40:57.087 align:start position:0%
and it's--you know, if you want
an accessible theme,

00:40:57.120 --> 00:40:58.555
go and have a look.

00:40:58.588 --> 00:40:59.823
You can select the themes.

00:40:59.856 --> 00:41:02.493
When you're doing review of the
themes on wordpress.org, you can

00:41:02.526 --> 00:41:06.530 align:start position:0%
select themes that have the tag
"accessibility ready,"

00:41:06.563 --> 00:41:11.268
and these ones probably are
better than many others.

00:41:11.301 --> 00:41:13.203
Allie: Wonderful.

00:41:13.236 --> 00:41:16.773
All right, next question, "It
helps a lot when a site uses a

00:41:16.806 --> 00:41:21.111
different color for visited
links, but how do you make

00:41:21.144 --> 00:41:22.646
that accessible?"

00:41:22.679 --> 00:41:25.249
Oh, so "It helps out when a site
uses a different color than the

00:41:25.282 --> 00:41:28.252
default shade of purple for
visited links, but how do you

00:41:28.285 --> 00:41:30.220
make that accessible?"

00:41:30.253 --> 00:41:32.489 align:start size:91% position:9%
Graham: Okay, well,
that's an interesting one.

00:41:32.522 --> 00:41:35.826
I mean, when you're choosing
colors for your links on your

00:41:35.859 --> 00:41:39.496
buttons and what have you,
I mean, you've got, I mean,

00:41:39.529 --> 00:41:41.832 align:start size:91% position:9%
in theory, like, almost an
infinite choice of what

00:41:41.865 --> 00:41:46.703 align:start position:0%
you can use, but it is important
for some people to know

00:41:46.736 --> 00:41:48.605
which links are visited.

00:41:48.638 --> 00:41:51.174 align:start size:97% position:3%
I wouldn't have said it was
one of the highest importance,

00:41:51.207 --> 00:41:52.843
accessibility issues.

00:41:52.876 --> 00:41:57.147
If I'm using a screen reader,
I use NVDA for a lot of my

00:41:57.180 --> 00:42:03.120
accessibility testing, and it
will tell me which links are

00:42:03.153 --> 00:42:05.055 align:start size:84% position:16%
visited and which
I've already visited.

00:42:05.088 --> 00:42:08.225 align:start size:91% position:9%
It will just say
so-so-link visited, okay?

00:42:08.258 --> 00:42:10.594 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, as a screen-reader user,
I know that I've

00:42:10.627 --> 00:42:13.263
already been there.

00:42:13.296 --> 00:42:15.399
Yeah, you can use
a different color.

00:42:15.432 --> 00:42:19.169 align:start position:0%
People would have to learn
the default colors, like, for--

00:42:19.202 --> 00:42:22.139 align:start size:94% position:6%
are blue for links that you
haven't visited yet

00:42:22.172 --> 00:42:24.474
and purple for links
that you have visited.

00:42:24.507 --> 00:42:27.311
Now, obviously, people wanna,
you know, use something that's

00:42:27.344 --> 00:42:31.048
in their brand palette, but I
wouldn't get too hung up about,

00:42:31.081 --> 00:42:35.319 align:start position:0%
you know, indicating
visited links too much, really.

00:42:35.352 --> 00:42:37.854
Yeah, just choose the color
that--if you want to indicate

00:42:37.887 --> 00:42:41.658 align:start size:94% position:6%
them, then choose a separate
color from the other one.

00:42:41.691 --> 00:42:44.761 align:start size:91% position:9%
But you know, don't
worry too much about that.

00:42:44.794 --> 00:42:46.730
Allie: Awesome.

00:42:46.763 --> 00:42:49.866 align:start size:94% position:6%
The next question, "Graham,
do you have any tips

00:42:49.899 --> 00:42:53.737
for an upcoming new
WordPress developer?"

00:42:53.770 --> 00:42:57.174 align:start size:81% position:19%
Graham: Okay,
yeah, good question.

00:42:57.207 --> 00:43:01.478 align:start position:0%
I was in that role at one point,
and you know, maybe I need

00:43:01.511 --> 00:43:03.280
to be learning it all again now.

00:43:03.313 --> 00:43:05.148
There's Gutenberg around.

00:43:05.181 --> 00:43:10.120 align:start position:0%
But yeah, in the theme
review guidelines, there's a lot

00:43:10.153 --> 00:43:13.090 align:start size:91% position:9%
of--yeah, there are a lot
code standards now,

00:43:13.123 --> 00:43:15.459
coding standards now.

00:43:15.492 --> 00:43:20.230
That includes a section on how
to build an accessible theme.

00:43:20.263 --> 00:43:24.267
It's got, like, it's--I didn't
really have much of a hand in

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:27.437 align:start size:97% position:3%
crafting this at all, but I
know that other members of the

00:43:27.470 --> 00:43:31.742
accessible team have had a lot
to do with it, and it's worth

00:43:31.775 --> 00:43:34.778
having a look because it's got
some real--really good tips in

00:43:34.811 --> 00:43:37.681
there and talks about some of
the issues that I covered in my

00:43:37.714 --> 00:43:43.120
presentation, and it explains
from a developer's perspective

00:43:43.153 --> 00:43:46.456
more about how to actually do
that in the themes that you're

00:43:46.489 --> 00:43:49.826
building, so I recommend that
you start with the, you know,

00:43:49.859 --> 00:43:53.163 align:start size:97% position:3%
the WordPress theme
coding guidelines and then the

00:43:53.196 --> 00:43:57.267 align:start position:0%
accessibility standards as
well, how theme developers would

00:43:57.300 --> 00:43:59.636 align:start size:97% position:3%
get--yeah, would work towards
getting that

00:43:59.669 --> 00:44:02.305
accessibility ready tag.

00:44:02.338 --> 00:44:05.142 align:start size:81% position:19%
Allie: Wonderful.
All right, next one.

00:44:05.175 --> 00:44:06.677
This one is a little bit long.

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:08.779 align:start size:88% position:13%
"It seems so many people
knowingly ignore

00:44:08.812 --> 00:44:10.681
accessibility altogether.

00:44:10.714 --> 00:44:14.451
If you could wave a magic wand
and immediately answer just one

00:44:14.484 --> 00:44:17.688
question mentioned during your
talk and never need to address

00:44:17.721 --> 00:44:21.391 align:start size:97% position:3%
it ever again, what would
you choose to make the biggest

00:44:21.424 --> 00:44:23.794
positive impact and why?

00:44:23.827 --> 00:44:29.166
Keyboard focus, interaction,
tab order, links, et cetera?"

00:44:29.199 --> 00:44:31.201
Graham: Okay, I'm gonna have
to say it's one of the keyboard

00:44:31.234 --> 00:44:36.540 align:start size:97% position:3%
ones here, and whether it's--
yeah, visible focus is--

00:44:36.573 --> 00:44:39.776
it's just vital for--
you know, the actual--

00:44:39.809 --> 00:44:42.479 align:start size:94% position:6%
people think of blind people
using the web.

00:44:42.512 --> 00:44:44.481
Yeah, and that's obviously
gonna be a bit difficult,

00:44:44.514 --> 00:44:47.651 align:start size:91% position:9%
and then yes, they can use
a screen reader, okay?

00:44:47.684 --> 00:44:53.824
But actually, the population of
people who are sighted but who

00:44:53.857 --> 00:44:57.194
have to use a keyboard or who
choose to use a keyboard--

00:44:57.227 --> 00:45:00.530
I actually got into IT when
these things like, you know,

00:45:00.563 --> 00:45:03.767
"Here's my mouse," these
things didn't exist, right?

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:06.570 align:start position:0%
It was all black and green
screens and keyboard keystrokes,

00:45:06.603 --> 00:45:08.438
and whatever, like that.

00:45:08.471 --> 00:45:10.340 align:start size:94% position:6%
I'm still a bit of a
power-keyboard user myself,

00:45:10.373 --> 00:45:16.079 align:start size:97% position:3%
so I would say visible focus,
you know, is vital for--

00:45:16.112 --> 00:45:19.449
you know, and making sure that
people can get to everywhere,

00:45:19.482 --> 00:45:22.285 align:start size:91% position:9%
everything, anything
that's a button or a link.

00:45:22.318 --> 00:45:26.456
Sometimes things pretend to be
a button, and they receive a--

00:45:26.489 --> 00:45:28.792 align:start size:91% position:9%
you can click on 'em,
but you can't actually tab

00:45:28.825 --> 00:45:30.560
to them, right?

00:45:30.593 --> 00:45:34.131 align:start size:97% position:3%
So keyboard--visible keyboard
focus and keeping focus

00:45:34.164 --> 00:45:36.233
in the right place.

00:45:36.266 --> 00:45:39.202
That's gonna be the one, really.

00:45:39.235 --> 00:45:40.670
Allie: Wonderful.

00:45:40.703 --> 00:45:42.272 align:start size:91% position:9%
All right, we've got about
three minutes left,

00:45:42.305 --> 00:45:44.407
so we've got time
for a couple more.

00:45:44.440 --> 00:45:47.177
I think this one's my favorite
so far: "Is there a way to do

00:45:47.210 --> 00:45:51.081 align:start size:84% position:16%
an accessible image
carousel or slideshow?

00:45:51.114 --> 00:45:56.520 align:start position:0%
Graham: Mm, yeah, okay, a
lot of companies that I've been

00:45:56.553 --> 00:45:58.755
working with--and there are
some big organizations now--

00:45:58.788 --> 00:46:02.259
are actually moving away from
using carousels because a lot

00:46:02.292 --> 00:46:05.762
of people--you know, see, there
are people that think they're

00:46:05.795 --> 00:46:07.731 align:start size:97% position:3%
a good idea, but there's a lot
of people who don't think

00:46:07.764 --> 00:46:09.432
they're a good idea.

00:46:09.465 --> 00:46:13.003
The short answer is it's
tricky, but it is possible.

00:46:13.036 --> 00:46:17.073
I mentioned the WCAG Guidelines.

00:46:17.106 --> 00:46:21.478
If you look on the Web
Accessibility Initiative

00:46:21.511 --> 00:46:27.751
website, it's got some useful
pages that show accessible

00:46:27.784 --> 00:46:32.289 align:start size:88% position:13%
examples of things like,
you know, carousels,

00:46:32.322 --> 00:46:34.791
drop down navigation.

00:46:34.824 --> 00:46:39.296
They've also got accordions,
tab panels, and what have you,

00:46:39.329 --> 00:46:41.731
and you know, track those down.

00:46:41.764 --> 00:46:45.035
I don't know if I put that--I
haven't got the link handy at

00:46:45.068 --> 00:46:50.140 align:start size:97% position:3%
the moment, but maybe I can
stick it in later on some way.

00:46:50.173 --> 00:46:53.810 align:start position:0%
They've got an example carousel,
and it's fairly good from an

00:46:53.843 --> 00:46:55.545
accessibility perspective.

00:46:55.578 --> 00:46:58.682
It can be used by keyboard
users, touchscreen users,

00:46:58.715 --> 00:47:01.418 align:start size:97% position:3%
screen-reader users, and also
let's not forget people

00:47:01.451 --> 00:47:03.720 align:start size:91% position:9%
who use voice recognition
software like Dragon

00:47:03.753 --> 00:47:05.755
Naturally Speaking as well.

00:47:05.788 --> 00:47:08.558
It's important that you--I
didn't mention that at all

00:47:08.591 --> 00:47:12.095 align:start position:0%
either, but it's important that
everything that you build

00:47:12.128 --> 00:47:14.764 align:start size:91% position:9%
can be actioned by people
who use those tools.

00:47:14.797 --> 00:47:20.203
So, you know, yeah, there are
accessible patterns out there,

00:47:20.236 --> 00:47:23.506
and it's useful to follow those.

00:47:23.539 --> 00:47:25.175
Allie: Wonderful.

00:47:25.208 --> 00:47:26.710 align:start size:97% position:3%
All right, we have one minute
left, so we can squeeze

00:47:26.743 --> 00:47:28.411
one more in, I think.

00:47:28.444 --> 00:47:30.046 align:start size:88% position:13%
Graham: All right,
I'll make it a quickie.

00:47:30.079 --> 00:47:31.314
Allie: Wonderful.

00:47:31.347 --> 00:47:33.750
Last question, "Would you like
to see accessibility standards

00:47:33.783 --> 00:47:36.353 align:start size:94% position:6%
for WordPress plugins,
and if so, how do you think

00:47:36.386 --> 00:47:38.388
we could apply them?"

00:47:38.421 --> 00:47:40.156
Graham: Okay, good question.

00:47:40.189 --> 00:47:43.526
Short answer is, yes, I would,
that whilst there are guidelines

00:47:43.559 --> 00:47:47.564 align:start size:91% position:9%
for theme builders on
accessibility, there is no

00:47:47.597 --> 00:47:50.734 align:start size:88% position:13%
guidance at all for
plugin builders at all.

00:47:50.767 --> 00:47:54.404
And plugins, as we've seen with
the lightbox in my presentation

00:47:54.437 --> 00:47:57.140
and also contact forms
can completely mess up

00:47:57.173 --> 00:47:59.476
the accessibility
of your website,

00:47:59.509 --> 00:48:03.213 align:start size:81% position:19%
so it's like the
Wild West out there.

00:48:03.246 --> 00:48:04.981
Allie: Fantastic.
Wonderful, Graham.

00:48:05.014 --> 00:48:06.449
Thank you so much.

00:48:06.482 --> 00:48:08.418 align:start size:91% position:9%
That's right on our time,
and thank you all.

00:48:08.451 --> 00:48:10.086 align:start size:91% position:9%
Graham: Thank you, Allie.
Allie: Absolutely.

00:48:10.119 --> 00:48:11.655 align:start size:91% position:9%
Graham: Cheers, everyone.
Take care, bye-bye.

00:48:11.688 --> 00:48:13.189
Allie: Bye-bye.

00:48:13.222 --> 00:48:15.125 align:start size:94% position:6%
And thank you all, everyone
watching, for attending

00:48:15.158 --> 00:48:17.093 align:start size:88% position:13%
"So How Do I Know If My
WordPress Website

00:48:17.126 --> 00:48:19.296 align:start size:81% position:19%
is Accessible?"
with Graham and me.

